text:
Regional Geology  
 The  Ten  Mile  Well  tenements  lie  within  the  Kalgoorlie  Terrane  of  the  Archaean  Yilgarn 
 Craton of Western Australia. The Kalgoorlie Terrane is situated centrally in the highly economic 
 [Ni  –Cu  –  (PGE),  Au]  Eastern  Goldfields  Superterrane  of  the  Archaean  Yilgarn  Craton.  The 
 Eastern  Goldfields  Superterrane  comprises  approximately  northnorthwest-  trending,  linear 
 greenstone  belts  of  metamorphosed  felsic,  mafic  and  ultramafic  volcanic  and  intrusive  rocks, 
 together with associated epiclastic, including volcaniclastic sedimentary rocks (Trofimovs, et. al, 
 2006). The greenstone succession was emplaced primarily between 2720 and 2655 Ma. Granitic 
 intrusion  coincided  with  the  later  stages  of  greenstone  formation,  with  a  period  of  high-Ca 
 granite intrusion between 2670 and 2655 Ma, and a second phase of low-Ca granite and alkaline 
 intrusion  post-dating  greenstone  formation,  between  2650  and  2630  Ma.  A  dominant  feature 
 within  the  Eastern  Goldfields  Superterrane  is  the  Norseman  –Wiluna  Greenstone  Belt,  which 
 extends ~600 km from Wiluna in the north to Norseman in the south. Major, postdepositional 
 faults  extend  for  hundreds  of  kilometres  along  the  north-northwest  strike  of  the  Norseman  –
 Wiluna  Greenstone  Belt,  and  a  minimum  of  two  phases  of  regional  folding  produced  steeply 
 dipping  contacts  in  the  greenstone  units.  The  metamorphic  grade  increases  from  prehnite  – 
 pumpellyite  facies  observed  in  the  north  at  Wiluna,  to  low-  to  mid-amphibolite  facies  further 
 south  (e.g.  at  Perseverance  in  the  Agnew  –Wiluna  Greenstone  Belt,  and  in  sections  of  the 
 Kalgoorlie Terrane).

24.text: The  Kalgoorlie  Terrane  lies  in  the  southern  section  of  the  Norseman  –Wiluna  Greenstone

25.text: Belt. The terrane encompasses a suite of granitic and greenstone units separated from adjacent

27.text: margin,  whereas  the  western  margin  is  bounded  by  the  regionally  extensive  Ida  Fault.
